INSERT INTO `fact` VALUES (1,2,'Belgium - Flanders                                          ',1,'','The Environmental Permit Decree (Article 20) states that the Flemish Government has the power to enact general environmental conditions or environmental conditions applying for each category of installation. First general binding rules were laid down that apply to all classified installations. Sectoral rules are also laid down for each category of installation. Rules therefore exist for all categories of installation.\r\nThese rules are enacted in the form of Flemish Government orders that supplement or amend the the title II of the Vlarem II .(IPPC reporting period 2003-2005, 2006)','same treatment for all installations, very usefull when there are many installations','','easy to change licenses','Before they were in an order, they exist already in general proposals for the authorithies.','','The experts-workgroups of Environmental Licenses division follows the BAT-evolutions continuously and prepare the necessary measures for theimplementation. Other authorities like the Air, Nuisance, Risk Management, Environment and Health Division make also proposals to change the general binding rules to maintain or meet environmental quality standards, to get info or to follow general sectoral plans etc.','','andere dingen','Hygiene and risk and nuisance management\r\nObligation to provide information\r\nWaste materials management and the management of installations that have been put out of operation\r\nThe storage of dangerous substances\r\nThe annual environmental report\r\nInternal company environmental protection\r\nSpecial committees of inquiry\r\nCONTROL OF GROUND AND GROUNDWATER POLLUTION\r\nCONTROL OF NOISE POLLUTION\r\nCONTROL OF NUISANCE DUE TO LIGHT\r\nCONTROL OF ASBESTOS','','the same as in the past','the general binding rules change often, normal more than two times a year\r\nbut they are a part of the licence\r\nso if the general binding rules change, all the concerned licenses change too\r\nthis is a very easy system to follow the quick evolutions',''),(2,2,'Belgium - Brussels                                          ',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(3,2,'Belgium - Walloon                                           ',1,'','General binding regulations take the form of the order of 4 july 2002 laying down the general operating conditions for facilities referred to in the decree of 11 March 1999 concerning environmental permits. This order covers all installations and activities, whatever their class. These GBRs are not ELVs.\r\nIn addition, sectoral conditions als permit the imposition of binding regulations on certain categories of installations. These conditions apply to the installations and activities of a particular economic or territorial sector or sector in which a specific hazard has or may appear. These sectors are designated by the Government (article 5, §2 of the decree of 11 March 1999 concerning environmental permits. (IPPC reporting 2003-2005)','GRBs enable te determine minimum environmental standard (includind ELVs) to be applied to installations','','','','','','','','','','','',''),(4,1,'Austria                                                     ',1,'','The report on the investigation of national IPPC permitting (AEAT, 2002) states that there are sectoral binding rules in Austria.\r\nEntec, 2006 (p.52 final report) states that some requirements are are laid down in generally applicable national legislation; the setting of permit conditions based on BAT is done on a case by case basis, unless included in general binding rules (e.g. ordinances).\r\nThe 2nd IPPC report states that with regards to the Austrian Provinces, the possibility of stipulating generally binding rules is either not explicitly provided for or this option was not utilised. For the most part, only a few IPPC installations are covered by the IPPC regime under provincial law.                                                                                                                                                                    Information on the name, type and dates of GBRs is sourced from the Investigation of national IPPC permitting (AEAT 2002) and the 2nd IPPC Report.\r\n\r\nData on the number of installations is taken from 2nd IPPC Report.','','','','The report on the Investigation of national IPPC permitting (AEAT, 2002) indicates that there was pre-existing national rules and guidance.','','Sometimes the starting point for the revision of GBR ordinances) is that they are considered as part of broader strategy to tackle current environmental problems with a significant impact (e.g. PM 10).','','','The GBRs are principally in the form of ELVs, however as is stated in the report \"Investigation of national IPPC permitting\" (AEAT, 2002), although there are no general rules or guidance for monitoring in Austria, if monitoring of emissions is required, the provisions are included in the respective laws or ordinances. Specific orders may contain binding release monitoring provisions. For example the Clean air act contains also the rules for monitoring of air emissions from boilers (e.g. frequency of measurements, amount of samples).','','redrafting in the water sector; see below','The 2nd IPPC Report states that in 2005, revision work began on several Orders with regard to continuing development of the respective state of the art and as regards the adaptation period which applies to existing IPPC operating installations (these Orders concern the areas \"Sintering of iron ore\", \"Iron and steel\", \"Non-ferrous metals\", \"Cement\" and \"Glass\"). \"The new ordinance for the limitation of air pollutants from the production of cement is to be published in the next weeks in the Federal Law Gazette (state of play: March 2007)',''),(5,3,'Bulgaria                                                    ',0,'Bulgaria has no definition for GBRs','When drafting the permits conditions GBRs can not be applied if the condition imposes requirement, which is an element of the BAT, or is connected to the controled technical characteristics of the abatement equipment, , or must be tailored specially for this permit. If the condition is indiferent to the specific permit and will simply repeat particular legislative text then this is avoided by refering to the legislative text itself. If a condition is written the above mentioned way - we consider it a GBR.','','','Incorporating GBRs is conv?nient tool to avoid unnecessary repetition of the legislation in the permit conditions. The use of GBRs facilitates both competent authorities and operators - first when writing the permit and second - when enforcing the permit. Additional relief is that unnecessary technical errors  when rewriting legislative text as a permit conditions are prevented.','','Before the implementation of the IPPC Directive Bulgaria used to carry out environmental audits of  the operational installations. The audit decissions contained conditions, some of which - in the shape of GBRs (according to the same principles described above)','After revision (or implementation of a new) of national legislative documents','','','','','Currently - no','',''),(6,4,'Cyprus                                                      ',1,'','IPPC 2nd reporting states that whilst national law does allow the possibility for laying down GBRs, no such rules have currently been esstablished.\r\n\r\nThe answer to Question 7.2.2 of the IPPC send reporting suggests that some guidance is defined in Cyprus.','','','','','','','','','','','','',''),(7,5,'Czech Republic                                              ',1,'','The IPPC 2nd Reporting states in answer to Question 8.2 that GBRs are not used in the Czech Republic. The answer to Question 7.2.2 suggests that guidance is defined.','','','GBRs are not used in the Czech Republic in the permitting process.  Binding Conditions                 of Operation for IPPC instalations are set individully. Binding Conditions are based on considerations on the use of BAT (general definition of BAT and BREFs), taking into account the technical characteristics of the installation, its location and local environmental conditions. The emission limits must not be less strict than the emission limits that would otherwise be laid down pursuant to the special regulations.','','','','','','','','','','General comment on amount of IPPC installations in the Czech Republic:\r\n\r\nData on total amount of installations in the Czech Republic are based on expert analysis from 2002. The Ministry of Environment in cooperation with czech IPPC Agency is working systematically on improvement of the data. In consequence of this activity numbers, which are available at the moment, are not fully identical with the data provided for the IPPC 2nd reporting.'),(8,6,'Denmark                                                     ',0,'','The Minister for the Environment can lay down binding rules for pollution from activities. Binding rules have been established for a number of IPPC installations e.g. combustion plants of 50MW or greater, waste incineration plants, disposal facilities, livestock farms. However, permit conditions are generally set on an installation-specific basis. (Entec, 2006) \r\nEmission to the air is regulated by EPA guidance nr. 6/1990 describin the control of air pollution from industrial installations. The principle of the Danish air emission legislation is that emission limit values are substances specific values and as such are not linked to specific industrial sectors or activites except for the waste incineration and the energy combustion sectors. The emission values are advisory national values, however if other emission values are to be used, it must be based on documentation of certain specific conditions. (AEAT, 2002)\r\nAt the time the country profile has been drawn up, the information on the 2nd IPPC reporting period (2003-2005) was not translated in English yet for Denmark. As soon as this information becomes available the country profile will be reviewed. You are, however, already invited to complete the profile for those topics that are not covered in the IPPC questionnaire (see questions 1, 3,4,5,6 and 7).','','','','','','','','','','','','',''),(9,7,'Estonia                                                     ',0,'law or subsidiary legal act, which contains limit values for polluting substances emmitted into ambient air and sewages  or waterbodies. Permit conditions for IPPC installations are based on BAT associated emission and consumption levels.','While some emission limit values are set in legislation, permit conditions are determined on an installation-specific basis. (Entec, 2006). Case-by-case. Need of General binding rules for cattle farms are under consideretion. (Dresden, 2005) Estonian legislation does not enable it.  (IPPC-permitting period 2003-2005, 2006).  The national level guidance, which contains als BAT suggestions are available from autumn 2006','','','Agree with all simplification matters, but in our circumstances GBR by branches does not provide such kind of advantages, because in the branch commonly only one or very few installations. Also GBR is quite rigid and continnuos improvement is more difficult.','','','','','','','','As it shown under point 9 only two categories (LCP and pig farms) deservs  efforts to design GBR as base for setting permit conditions. But taking into account how different fuels is used in combustion plants (oil shales, natural gas, biomass, heavy fuel oil) it is better to set integrated permit conditions case by case and guided by LCP and other relevant BREFs.  Pig farms are located in rural areas with different local conditions. So, GBR seems to be too rigig, but ILF BREF provides good possibilities to introduce BAT and minimize negative impacts to the surrounding environment.','no','no'),(10,8,'Finland                                                     ',0,'','BAT is assessed on an installation-specific basis (ENTEC, 2006) However, it is possible to lay down certain requirements for certain categories of insallations in general binding rules by Government decree (section 12 of the EPA). Also reference is made to the implementation of the VOC-Directive, the LCP-Directive and the 2000/76/EC Directive on waste incineration  as a way of applying GBRs.(IPPC-implementation 2003-2005, 2006)','','','','','','','','','','','','',''),(11,9,'France                                                      ',1,'',' The general binding rules for any sector or activity are stated in the pertinent sectoral ministerial orders. These orders set maximum emission limit values for all the pollutants characteristic of the sector, which may be adapted to local conditions by the permit, as well as the general principles that must be observed in the operation of the installation. All sectors of IPPC are covered by such a ministerial decree. These orders have a wider scope than IPPC and set rules for non-IPPC activities. In some cases, the orders do not map directly on to the sectoral coverage of the IPPC Directive so it is necessary to search through a number of orders to determine all the emission limit values that apply to a particular sector. The values set on a case by case basis in the permit can be set at a more restrictive level than defined in these orders, depending on the characteristics of the discharges and the sensitivity of the environmental receptor.','','','','','','','','','The GBR adresse all the environmental issues such as waste, soil protection, noise, vibrations, etc.','','No','We consider that GBRs are very efficient tools which decrease the time necessary to draft the conditions of the permits',''),(12,10,'Germany                                                     ',1,'','Appendix B of the EC DG Env study on Assessment of the implementation by member states of the IPPC Directive (Entec, 2006) states that the GBRs are laid out in a national central body of rules governing the determination of ELVs and other emission-limiting requirements relating to air and water quality for licensable installations. These include the statutory orders (Bundes-Immissionsschutzverordnungen – BImSchVs) and associated non-statutory ordinances\r\n(Technische Anleitungen – TAs). These instructions explain in detail the requirements which the CAs should take into account when granting licences for industrial and commercial installations. The Wastewater Ordinance (Abwasserverordnung - AbwV) based on the WHG contains annexes for more than 50 sectors prescribing sector-specific stipulations and standards (ELVs). These requirements represent GBRs valid for the whole sector and for all of Germany. While BAT standards outlined in the BREFs have already been incorporated into the revised TA Luft, the BAT requirements outlined in the BREFs for wasterwater emissions have not yet fully been incorporated into the GBRs laid out in the annexes of the AbwV.','','','','','','','','','','EC DG Env, Assessment of the implementation by member states of the IPPC Directive (Entec, 2006) states that BREF documents are taken into consideration by the (BMU) when determining GBRs. In addition it states that regulations do not prescribe any specific technique, but contain ELVs which have to be met. Specific techniques may also be specified in order to define a particular level of pollution control or abatement in accordance with BAT.\r\n\r\nWith regard to monitoring, Appendix 3 of the Investigation of national IPPC permitting (AEAT, 2002) states that  TA-Luft. gives guidance on the measurement of emissions from some plant. For dust-like, gaseous and vaporous emissions there is a requirement for continuous measurements when certain massflows are exceeded.','','At the time of compiling this draft country profile, the German implementation report for 2003-2005 was available in German only. See http://cdr.eionet.europa.eu/de/eu/ippc.  The 2nd Implementation Report states that the central regulation for the setting of emission limit requirements to air for facilities requiring an IPPC permit is the TA Luft. Discrete statutory orders give emission limits for certain substances from specific types of plant.','The 2nd Implementation Report also states that for direct discharges of effluent to water, the Wastewater Ordinance contains requirements for the analysis and measurement and in the annex emission limits for effluent discharges from numerous sources. Additional requirements exist within the Bundesländer for discharges to water from public sewage treatment works.'),(13,11,'Greece                                                      ',1,'','National law does not at present contain the possibility of laying down certain requirements for certain categories of installations in general binding rules instead of including them in individual permit conditions(IPPC implementation 2000-2002,2003).\r\nStandard ELVs are defined for a variety of pollutants in relevant Presidential Decrees and in Prefectural Decisions (for emissions to water only). Nevertheless, these standard ELVs are not binding for the CA, that has the right to impose stricter ELVs on the basis of (a) specific impacts caused to the environment, (b) expected performance of implemented BATs, (c) general environmental conditions at a specific geographical area, (d) demands by local authority or/and the public (ENTEC, 2006).\r\nGreek industry is of a rather small size. Actual national GBRs concern air emissions of certain sectors (mainly: combustion plants, cement production and refineries) and liquid wastes.','','','','Every GBR resulting from the Community Right (e.g. LCPD, solvents use Directive) is applied.','Generally, Greek GBRs are based on Presidential Decree 1180/81 (GG 293A) concerning air pollutants and on the relative Prefectural Decission concerning liquid wastes. Especially for industrial and domestic boilers, GBRs concern soot and CO2 emissions, as well as monitoring (Joint Ministerial Decisions 11294/93 (GG 264B) and 10315/93 (GG 369B).','','','','Maintenance requirements concerning industrial and domestic boilers and energy efficiency limit values concerning domestic boilers.','','Yes. Reconsider the PD 1180/81.','',''),(14,12,'Hungary                                                     ',1,'','General emission limit values are set in media-specific legislation. These ELVs represent the minimum criteria for meeting BAT. Permit conditions are set on an installation specific basis. (Entec, 2006) The Hungarian law does contain the possibility of laying down GBRs. These are technological emission limits, and they specify the minimum requirements to be fulfilled. Most of the legislation which established GBRs are media-based and super-sectoral. Examples of this are the Govt. Decree 21/2001. (II. 14.) on the monitoring and reporting of air emissions, the Joint KöM-EüM-FVM Decree 14/2001 (V.9.) on air pollution limit values and the KvVM Decree 28/2004 (XII. 25) on limits pertaining to the emission of water pollutants and the 10/2000. (VI.2.) KöM-EÜM-FVM-KHVM Joint Decree on the ELVs necessary for the protection of groundwater and soil quality. Also reference is made to the implementation of the LCP Directive (KvVM Decree 10/2003), the VOC Directive (KöM Decree 10/2001 (IV. 19.)) and the EU Directive on waste incineration (KöM Decree 3/2002 (II. 22.) which has lead to the introduction of GBRs for the industries referred to. Installations engaged in agricultural activities in nitrate sensitive areas must comply with the rules of Good agricultural Practice (GAP), set out in the 27/2006. (II.7.) FVM Decree on the protection of water against pollution from agriculture.   (IPPC-implementation 2003-2005, 2006). There is also a super-sectoral KöM-EüM Joint Decree on the setting of noise and vibration ELVs, the 8/2002. (III.22.).','','','Some of the GBRs mentioned are transposed EU-Directives. This is the case for the VOC-Directive (KöM Decree 10/2001 (IV. 19.)), the LCP Directive (KvVM Decree 10/2003 (VII.11.) and the Directive on waste incineration (KöM Decree 10/2001 (IV. 19.)','','','','','','','','','',''),(15,13,'Ireland                                                     ',0,'','Section 86(4) of the Environmental Protection Agency Acts 1992 and 2003 allow for the regulation of certain types of installations or classes of activities by way of general binding rules (GBRs) in accordance with Article 9(8) of the IPPC Directive. However, GBRs have not been established for any category of installation and the permitting of installations listed in Annex 1 of the Directive are accomplished on a case by case basis with reference to national BAT Guidance notes.','','','','','','','','','','','','',''),(16,14,'Italy                                                       ',1,'','Sectorial GBRs exist for different environmental media (air, water, noise,…) and they appy to IPPC and no IPPC installations, however the criterion at the base of those rules don’t take in account the integrated approach and the BAT identification, then they generally can not be considered sufficient to set permit conditions for IPPC installations.\r\nOn the basis of BREFs and national guidelines, Italy is checking out the possibility to set IPPC GBR up for certain sectors, but the need to take in account local conditions finding out BAT seems a critical issue .','Grant a minimum level of environmental performance','Even “multiple media” GBRs could have difficulties to take in account properly cross media impacts, in particular when in the specific situation some media has a critic level of quality and other a very good one.','The use of GBRs introduce significant restraint to the application of the IPPC. It means:\r\n-	less work for the competent authority\r\n-	clear indication for operators\r\n-	uniform application of the law\r\nbut also-\r\n-	permit asset who don’t fit perfectly the local (installation-surround) situation\r\n-	risk to loose of the “continue improvement” needs of the IPPC directive\r\n-	risk to introduce a market distortion and/or an inappropriate use of resouces, generally promoting investment to abate some specific pollutants without a clear evidence, descending from a cross media analisys, those polluttants are really the critic ones in the specific contest.','As above explained, in Italy GBR apply generally to IPPC and not IPPC installations, and are generally not sufficient to set IPPC permit conditions.','','','','','','','As above explained, the possibility to adopt IPPC GBR (based on BREF and national Guidelines) is at the study.','',''),(17,15,'Latvia                                                      ',1,'','Permit conditions are set on an installation specific basis (ENTEC, 2006), When specifying the conditions for the issue of an IPPC permit, the provisions within relevant laws and regulations relating to a specific installations operations are taken into account. Latvias laws and regulations foresee the inclusion of the specific requirements of general binding rules for a few categories of installations. The Cabinet of Ministers can issue general binding rules, foreseeing requirements relating to specific installations and their operations, based on the Law on Pollution and the authority included in the Law on Waste Management. Accordingly GBRs for the large combustion plants (implementation of LCP-Directive), installations utilising VOC (implementation of the VOC-Directive) and for waste collection facilities and waste incineration installations are adpoted by Cabinet of Ministers(IPPC-reporting 2003-2005, 2006).','','','','BAT guidance (BREF, BAT Reference Notes developed by World Bank Group`s “Pollution Prevention and Abatement Handbook”,  Batnees Guidance Notes developed by the Irish Environmental Protection Agency and HELCOM Recommendations) is used since IPPC implementation.','','In accordance with changes in other related national legal acts.','','','Control and reporting obligations','','The question is open','','According to Annex 7 (point 1) of Cabinet of Ministers Regulation No 294 adopted on July 9, 2002 \"On Application of Category A, B and C Polluting Activities and Permitting of Category A and B Polluting Activities\" permit conditions for the polluting activity are set in compliance with provisions of legal acts of the environment protection (Cabinet of Ministers Regulations) that, taking into account deffinition of GBR, could be considered as GBRs. The legal acts of the environmental protection are available: http://www.vidm.gov.lv/lat/likumdosana/'),(18,16,'Lithuania                                                   ',1,'','No general binding rules have been adopted. (Entec, 2006) A possibility of the issuance of general rules for the protection of the environment is spelled out in the IPPC Rules, but so far no such rules have been drawn up for the economic activities and installations of Annex I. (IPPC reporting period 2003-2005, 2006)','','','','','','','','','','','It is concidered to develop GBR for non - IPPC installations, for example wood processing, car services, water usage and etc.','',''),(19,17,'Luxembourg                                                  ',0,'','Pre-existing national guidance for air emissions is supplemented by guidance from other countries for water/land. In future it is planned to use BREF notes in parallel with this existing guidance. (AEAT, 2002). There is no additional information in the Luxembourg IPPC reporting for the period 2003-2005','','','','','','','','','','','In future it is planned to use BREF notes in parallel with this existing guidance. (AEAT, 2002).','',''),(20,18,'Malta                                                       ',0,'','At the time the country profiles has been drawn up, the information on the 2nd IPPC reporting period (2003-2005) was not available yet for Malta. As soon as this information becomes available the country profile will be reviewed. You are, however, already invited to complete the profile for those topics that are not covered in the IPPC questionnaire (see questions 1, 3,4,5,6 and 7).','','','','','','','','','','','','',''),(21,19,'Netherlands                                                 ',1,'','The Netherlands has many mandatory general regulations that apply to IPPC installations.\r\n\r\n1. Decree BEES A (Besluit emissie-eisen stookinstallaties A), implementation of  LCP Directive 2001/80\r\n2. Air emissions - waste incineration - decree (Besluit verbranden afvalstoffen), implementation of Waste Incineration Directive 2000/76\r\nThese decrees apply to combustion installations in several sectors. The table under 9. is in that respect not complete. BEES A applies for example also to pulp, paper and cartbord (catergorie 6.1).\r\nThese decrees determine general emission requirements.(IPPC-implementation 2003-2005, 2006). Since the last couple of months however, less use has been made from the ELVs in these decrees but a case-by case approach has been applied, also in view of recent verdicts of the State Advisory Council. As a result therof the competent authorities determine for each individual installation emission limit values that reflect best available techniques using among several information sources the BREFs. The decrees function more as a safety net.\r\n\r\nOther examples:\r\n3. Decree on Emission requirements for NOx for nitric acid installations (Besluit emissie-eisen NOx Salpeterzuurfabrieken). This decree will be repealed. Emission limit values for this sector are in practice already determined by a case-by-case approach based on the BAT values defined in the relevant BREFs.\r\n\r\n4. Decree on Landfill Sites and Landfill Bans (Besluit stortplaatsen en stortverboden afvalstoffen), implementation of 1999/31/EC\r\n5. Soil Protection Landfill Sites Decree (Stortbesluit bodembescherming), implementation of 1999/31/EC\r\n\r\n6. Decree on Outdoor Manure Storage (Besluit mestbassins milieubeheer), applies to categorie 6.6 (poultry, pigs, sows)\r\n7. Act Ammonia and Livestock Farming (Wet ammoniak en veehouderij), applies to categorie 6.6 (poultry, pigs, sows). The act gives guidelines on how competent authorities should take into account the geographical location and local environmental conditions (article 9.4 IPPC Drective) when determining emission limit values to protect nature protection areas.\r\n8. Act Odour Nuisance and Livestock Farming (Wet geurhinder en veehouderij), applies to categorie 6.6 (poultry, pigs, sows). The act gives guidelines on how competent authorities should take into account the geographical location and local environmental conditions (article 9.4 IPPC Drective) when determining emission limit values to prevent en reduce odour nuisance.\r\n9. In development: Decree on animal housing (Besluit ammoniakemissie huisvesting veehouderij). The decree regulates emission limit values for ammonia from animal houses\r\n\r\n10. Article 8.40 Environmental Management Act Decrees. The Netherlands has a long history in formulating GBRs in combination with a permit exemption for non-IPPC installations. 13 decrees regulate around 300.000 small and medium sized businesses. Both industry and competent authorities support this approach. It makes legisation more clear and transparant and reduces administrative burden for both industry and competent authorities. This facilitates smooth implementation and enables realizing meeting environmental targets.The approach includes a possibility for the competent authorities to require additional and case-by-case measures based on the geographical location and local environmental conditions. \r\n11. In development: Activities Decree / Agriculture Decree. As a result of the broad support for the combination GBRs/permit exemptions the approach is extended to the metals/electro industry and a larger part of agriculture, including livestock below IPPC thresholds. Also as part of this project the article 8.40 Decree are integrated.The installations included in the extension will from 2008 on be regulated by general binding rules and are exempted from the permit obligation. Also as part of this project the 13 Article 8.40 Decrees are integrated into two decrees: Activities Decree / Agriculture Decree.\r\n\r\n12. Also guidelines have been developed to assist the CAs in their assessment of  BAT at each installations. For example: the Dutch Atmospheric Emissions Guideline (NeR) and the Commission on Integrated Water Management (CIW) guidelines . (ENTEC, 2006)','\r\n- Implementation of EU legislation, f.e. LCP D','GBRs under IPPC can in most case not be combined with a permit exemption','','','','Regular update (time not specified) depending on developments in best available techniques, developments/preferences in sector (f.e. more or less preference for level playing field), developments in environmental quality','','','Geographical location/local environmental conditions. See question 2. under 8 and 9 for clarification.','Currently the IPPC Directive limits the use of GBRs in combination with permit exemptions. The Netherlands are of the opinion that for relative simple and uniform industrial and agricultural activities general binding rules based on the IPPC Directive should be sufficient. The permit obligation of the IPPC Directive should no longer be required for those activities. This would make legisation more clear and transparant and reduce administatve burden for both industry and competent authorities, while maintaining a high level of environmental protection.','See question 2.\r\n\r\nDecree on animal housing (Besluit ammoniakemissie huisvesting veehouderij). The decree regulates emission limit values for ammonia from animal houses\r\n\r\nActivities Decree / Agriculture Decree. As a result of the broad support for the combination GBRs/permit exemptions the aproach is extended to the metals/electro industry and a larger part of agriculture, including livestock below IPPC thresholds. The installations included in the extension will from 2008 on be regulated by general binding rules and are exempted from the permit obligation. Also as part of this project the 13 Article 8.40 Decrees are integrated into two decrees: Activities Decree / Agriculture Decree.','- In 2002 a general evaluation of administrative burdens of environmental law was made, which also includes GBRs under IPPC (see chapter 4.3 in the attached report Nulmeting administratieve lasten Ministerie van VROM 2002). \r\n- In 2006 an economic analyses has been made of the consequences for competent authorities and industry of extending the use of general binding rules for non-IPPC installations in combination with a permit exemptions (see the attached reports Bestuurlijke lasten Activiteiten AMvB en Actal-toets Activiteiten AMvB).',''),(22,20,'Poland                                                      ',1,'','The IPPC 2nd Reporting states that GBRs are used for certain sectors in Poland. The GBRs are usually a consequence of transpositions of the provisions of European Union Directives to Polish Law  \r\nBesides there are several BAT guidances for some specific sectors. The guidance provides advice but are not binding (no legal basis).','','','','Poland used to have binding emmission standards (set up in the legal acts) before IPPC implementation.','legal acts are based on the transposition of directives, while guidances are based on BREFs conclusions and national BAT assessments','','','',' technical requirements for landfills','GBR set up in the legal acts usually refer to emission limit values, some other parameters (for example for waste waters: pH, temperature, BOT, ChOT), but also emission  monitoring requirements, and fand technical requirements (for landfills).\r\nSectoral BAT guidances refer as well to all the issues mentioned above.','We are considering preparing more sectoral guidances.','',''),(23,21,'Portugal                                                    ',0,'Regarding the scope of the Art. 9 (8) of theIPPC Directive, Portugal used to interpret GBR as specific regulation for particular sectors that regulate all its activity, hence, it would not be necessary an environment permit. In theses terms Portugal does not use GBR. \r\nHowever, in Portugal it exists specific legislation for determined activities, especially regarding ELV to water and air that we consider as minimum requirements for IPPC permits.\r\nThis concept is similar to the actual concept of GBR presented in this project.\r\nBesides that, in Portugal it exists legislation of general application, especially for ELV to water and air for all the sectors that do not have specific legislation. \r\nWe would like to stress that most of the specific sectorial legislation resulted from voluntary agreements based on the installations environmental performance and ELV set in these legislation will be considered in IPPC permits only until the 30th of Ocotber of 2007. From this date on, the IPPC installations must operate accordingly to the BAT associated emisson values set in the sectorial BREF. If BREF does not set any AEV,  IPPC installations are obliged to accomplish the ELV set on the general legislation as referred above. \r\nIn what concerns to this project, Portugal will consider GBR as the specific legislation for any particular sector and legislation of general application for the sectors that do not have specific legislation.','','transposition of directives','','','','Based on the performance of the installations.','','','','','','','','Number of installations referring to the 2003-2005 period as reported in the 2nd questionnaire for the IPPC Directive Implementation. Ordinance n.º 286/93, 12th of March includes both ELV of general application for all sectors and ELV for particular pollutants of determined sectors.'),(24,22,'Romania                                                     ',1,'','At present Romania applies the procedure and establishes the emissions limit values case by case. In future, the use of general binding rules could be considered. (2007, communication with Romanian Representative)','','','','','','','','','','','','',''),(25,23,'Slovakia                                                    ',1,'','Specific emission limits are defined for all industrial activity categories. Provision has a form of decree of MoE SR (No. 706/2002 Coll. as  amended). (IPPC-reporting 2003-2005, 2006).','','','','','','','','','','','no','','* General cross sectoral GBR for all instalations'),(26,24,'Slovenia                                                    ',1,'','Environmental legislation requires individual environmental permit for any industrial activity causing environmental burdens. The permit can be based on general binding rules, or BATAELVs, taking into account local conditions and environmental standards. Permitted emission values must not exceed ELV from national legislation (general binding rules) and must take into account BREF documents, geographical characteristics of the area, the state of the environment in the area of the installation and its technical characteristics. (Dresden, 2005) The national law does not provide for the application of general binding rules as substitute for IPPC permits. The general binding regulations must, of course, be complied with when defining the requirements of an IPPC permit, but only as minimum standards. They exist for all categories of IPPC installations and are mostly based on German and Austrian law (like TA Luft, Abwasserverordnung, TA Laerm etc.) or else transposed from EU law (large combustion installations, waste-incineration plants, TiO2, emissions of organic solvents, landfills etc.) (IPPC reporting period 2003-2005, 2006)','traditional approach','','Beside historical reasons there was also transposition of EU law that led to adoption of various decrees in the form of GBRs like LCPs, VOCs, TiO2 production, WI etc.','BAT requirements were included in GBRs in some extent under the term \"state of the art\"','GBRs were mostly transposed from EU states which have similar environmental legislation (Germany, Austria), now GBR are harmonised with BREF conclusions.','','','','water consumption and operational measures only in some sectors','GBRs in Slovenia are sectoral or cross-sectoral and further .media-specific or covering several media.\r\nExamples: \r\n-Decree on noise (noise levels in the environment, cross-sectoral, media-specific)\r\n-Decree on wastes from Tio2 production (emission of wastes and wastewaters; sectoral/several media)\r\n-Decree on air emissions from stationary sources (general emissions of subtances into the air, cross-sectoral/media specific\r\n-Decree on emissions of wastewaters from pulp and paper industry (emissions of certain substances in waters; sectoral/media specific)','at the begining of 2008 a Decree on odour will be issued','Beside cited legislation on ELV for air and water discharges in table 9 there is for all activities general legislation on noise, electromagnetic radiation, emissions to soil, emissions from water conditioning, cooling water etc, see weblink',''),(27,25,'Spain                                                       ',0,'not exactly the above mentioned definition. Generally speaking, this definition could be applied without the last sentence. If GBRs exist, they are always mandatory. In any case, the conditions established by the GBR, if applicable, are the maximum ones in order to guarantee the higest level of environmental protection','The application of GBRs in IPPC permits is a competence of the Autonomous Goverments, since they are the environmental conpetent authority.\r\nThe main aim of IPPC is to get the highest level of environmental protection. Having in mind this main principle, GBRs are usually applied for IPPC instalations when no references are given in BREF regarding BAT-based permit conditions or when the GBR conditions are more restrictive than the BAT-approach. Not all susbtances for every industrial activity are contemplated in BREF or BAT approach. So, in some cases it is necessary to consider or to apply GBRs, mainly when no emission values are shown in BAT or BREF. Taking into acount local conditions (special areas of protection or areas with very restrictive environmental legislations) or technical characteristics of the installation, GBRs could be included in IPPC permits if they guarantee a higher level of protecction than those just applying IPPC BAT-based permit conditions','In IPPC permits, GBRs are usually considered when there are not shown specific conditions in BREF or under BAT-approach. Also, in some sectors where the sectorial legislation is much more restrictive than BAT conditions. Also GBRs apply for some subtances to specific media (emissions to water, mainly)','','From our point of view GBRs and IPPC are not antagonistic systems. BAT aproach does not have to be the best one in every case or in every place. For instance, in some cases and in some areas the ELV allowed can be lower than the BAT-AEV. In these cases the application of GBRs guarantee a higer level of environmental protection than BAT.\r\nThis is completely in line with the IPPC objectives: the local and technical characteristics shall be considered. This point is not clearly contemplated in this questionary','As an example of GBRs established after IPPC transposition should be mentioned the european legislation on ETS, which does not allow to fix ELV for the CO2 emissions in IPPC permits.','there is no a general procedure to establish a specific GBR. Sometimes through the updating of current legislation, transposition of Directives, establishing new pieces of legislation, etc','depends on the type of legislation, GBR to be revised, sector implied, subtances, etc…','','','','All this issues could be adressed in GBRs as well as in IPPC permits.\r\nFrom our point of view GBRs and IPPC are not antagonistic systems. BAT aproach does not have to be the best one in every case or in every place. For instance, in some cases and in some areas the ELV allowed can be lower than the BAT-AEV. In these cases the application of GBRs guarantee a higer level of environmental protection than BAT.\r\nThis is completely in line with IPPC objectives: the local and technical characteristics shall be considered. This point is not clearly contemplated in this questionary','GBRs could be defined in the future.','Some examples could be considered as a kind of GBRS, as previous legislation on ELVs that are considered as minimum requirements',''),(28,26,'Sweden                                                      ',1,'However, the intention is not that the GBR:s are to be used directly to set permit conditions.','Under Chapter 9, Section 5 of the environmental Code, the Government can, in the matter of hazardous acitivities issue regulations on prohibitions, protective measures, restrictions and other precautionary measures, if this appears more practical than decisions on individual case. The Government can also delegate the issuing of such regulations to an authority if there are particular reasons to do so. So far, however, no general rules have been issued solely to comply with the IPPC Directive, and which cover all the aspects covered by the Directive. (IPPC implementation 2003-2005,2006)\r\n\r\nFor IPPC-installations there are no GBRs set whith the intention to be used directly as permit conditions. However, the minimum criteria in e.g. the LCP- and the WID-directives have been directly transposed into regulations as mimum standards.\r\nAny national guidelines on emission limits will only be informative in character, and not legally binding as each permit shall be evaluated on a case-specific basis. (AEAT, 2002) Emission Limit Values, ELVs, are in specific cases not derived from the with BAT Associated Emission Levels, AELs, in the BREFs. ELVs are derived from what is considered to be BAT in the specific case. When considering what is BAT in the particular case the BREF is taken into account.(On the Road to Sustainable Production in the Enlarged EU - Integrated Pollution Prevention and Control (IPPC), Dresden 2005)\r\n\r\n\r\nCould you please indicate the legal reference for these activities which may issue GBRs according to section 47 of the Decree (1998:899). The existance of GBRs for these activities and their legal reference is discussed in question 9. You can also upload a  relevant document or weblink to the Content Management System. The consultants will be able to amend the country profile themselves.\r\nHow to do this:\r\nLog on with the Swedish account. Go to My Folder. Go to subfolders \"Background documents\" or \"Useful links\". Choose in \"Add to folder\" (in green bar) add file or link. Upload the file or link.','transposition of EC legislation','','','','','','','','','Under Chapter 9, Section 5 of the environmental Code, the Government can, in the matter of hazardous acitivities issue regulations on prohibitions, protective measures, restrictions and other precautionary measures, if this appears more practical than decisions on individual case. (IPPC implementation 2003-2005,2006)','','',''),(29,27,'UK                                                          ',1,'','The UK does not use GBRs as defined by the IPPC Directive. However, it does produce sectoral guidance, soemtimes referred to \"standard rules\" for limited types of activities - the main example is the agricultural sector for intensive animal units (Annex 1 ref - 6.6).  These may be described as \"GBR like\".\r\n\r\nFor other sectors guidance is defined and is applied by the competant authority. Applicants for PPC permits are required to describe the techniques and their association environmental releases and compare these with the BAT benchmarks set out in the guidance. Deviations from the general guidance may only be permitted where it is accepted by the regulator that these will represent BAT in the specific circumstances of that installation. Economic factors are considered in the sectoral context. \r\n\r\nThis information has been obtained through dicussions with Richard Vincent of DEFRA (February 2007).','Used for intenisve animal rearing only - a major reason is that this sector has not been regulated before and therefore it will make it easier to permit the large number of installations. (Personal Communication with Richard Vincent (DEFRA), February 2007).','This information has been obtained through a Personal Communication with Richard Vencent (DEFRA), February 2007.','Historically the UK has adopted a systems of regulation that provides for some flexibility of precise permit conditions at a local level to allow site specific design and environmental factors to be taken into account. \r\nLegislative interia: it is considered that, in the UK context, defining BAT based permit conditions in national legislation would create additional time delays when that legislation requires review - it is considered that BAT is dynamic, requiring a general legislative permitting framework and the more expedient delivery provided for by guidance and permitting systems. Personal Communication with Richard Vincent (DEFRA) February 2007).','','','','','','','','','','');
